      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that the quantum state of one cannot be described independently of the others, even when separated by vast distances. It is fundamentally different from classical correlation because, in classical systems, correlations arise from pre-existing shared properties or hidden variables, whereas in quantum entanglement, the properties are not determined until measurement occurs, and the outcomes are correlated in a way that defies local realism.\n\nTo put it simply, if you have two entangled particles, measuring the spin of one instantly determines the spin of the other, regardless of the distance between them. This is often described as \"spooky action at a distance,\" a phrase coined by Einstein who was skeptical of the idea. In contrast, classical correlation is like having two gloves in separate boxes; if you open one and find a left glove, you know the other is a right glove, but the gloves already had those properties before you opened the boxes.\n\nEntanglement is a uniquely quantum feature that has no classical analog and is a key resource for quantum computing and cryptography. While classical correlations can be explained by local hidden variables, entanglement violates Bell's inequalities, proving that the universe cannot be described",
      "source": "target",
