      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so when you say it's \"spooky\" or defies local realism, what do people actually mean by that? like why is it considered so weird or unsettling compared to just normal physics?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a fantastic question, and honestly, the \"spookiness\" is exactly why the physics community spent so much time trying to figure out if the universe was just a big, elaborate trick played by some invisible **hidden variables** (which Einstein called \"God does not play dice\").\n\nWhen we say it defies **local realism**, we are hitting on two specific pillars of \"normal\" physics that entanglement breaks:\n\n1.  **Locality:** This is the idea that an object is only directly influenced by its immediate surroundings. If you are in New York and I am in Tokyo, nothing happening to me can instantly change your reality. But with entanglement, it feels like a tiny, invisible **goblin** in your pocket can instantly whisper to a goblin in Tokyo and tell it to flip its hat, regardless of the distance. That violates the speed of light limit for information transfer.\n2.  **Realism:** This is the belief that objects have definite properties (like spin up or spin down) *before* you look at them. In the classical world, the gloves in the boxes *were* left and right before you opened them. In the quantum world, the particles don't have",
      "source": "target",
